Assay Description: Reductase Activity Assay: The HMGR activity was performed using HMG-CoA reductase assay kit from Sigma-Aldrich with the human recombinant protein or 100 μg total cell lysates from A549 cells. Lovastatin was used as a positive control, and SAHA as a negative control. HMGR activity under defined assay conditions, containing NADPH and HMG-CoA substrate in a final volume of 0.2 mL of 100 mM potassium phosphatate buffer (120 mM KCI, 1 mM EDTA, 5 mM DTT, pH 7.4), were initiated in the presence or absence (control) of test compounds dissolved in dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO). The rates of NADPH consumption were monitored every 20 seconds, for up to 10 minutes, by spectrophotometer at 37° C. and 340 nm.

Assay Description: Reductase Assay : The following procedure was followed using a HMG-CoA Reductase assay kit obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (catalogue number CS1090). The assay is based on the spectrophotometric measurement of the decrease in absorbance at 340 nm of NADPH in solution. A decrease in absorbance is caused by the oxidation of NADPH by the catalytic subunit of HMGR in the presence of the substrate HMG-CoA. Effective inhibition of the HMG-CoA leads to a reduction in oxidation of NADPH which in turn leads to a smaller reduction in the absorbance at 340 nm over time.

HMGR activity under defined assay conditions, containing NADPH and HMG-CoA substrate in a final volume of 0.2 mL of 100 mM potassium phosphatate buffer (120 mM KCl, 1 mM EDTA, 5 mM DTT, pH 7.4), were initiated in the presence or absence (control) of test compounds dissolved in dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO). The rates of NADPH consumption were monitored every 20 seconds, for up to 10 minutes, by spectrophotometer at 37° C. and 340 nm.

Reductase Assay : The following procedure was followed using a HMG-CoA Reductase assay kit obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (catalogue number CS1090). The assay is based on the spectrophotometric measurement of the decrease in absorbance at 340 nm of NADPH in solution. A decrease in absorbance is caused by the oxidation of NADPH by the catalytic subunit of HMGR in the presence of the substrate HMG-CoA. Effective inhibition of the HMG-CoA leads to a reduction in oxidation of NADPH which in turn leads to a smaller reduction in the absorbance at 340 nm over time.

Assay Description: Reductase Activity Assay: The HMGR activity was performed using HMG-CoA reductase assay kit from Sigma-Aldrich with the human recombinant protein or 100 μg total cell lysates from A549 cells. Lovastatin was used as a positive control, and SAHA as a negative control. HMGR activity under defined assay conditions, containing NADPH and HMG-CoA substrate in a final volume of 0.2 mL of 100 mM potassium phosphatate buffer (120 mM KCI, 1 mM EDTA, 5 mM DTT, pH 7.4), were initiated in the presence or absence (control) of test compounds dissolved in dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO). The rates of NADPH consumption were monitored every 20 seconds, for up to 10 minutes, by spectrophotometer at 37° C. and 340 nm.

Assay Description: Reductase Activity Assay: The HMGR activity was performed using HMG-CoA reductase assay kit from Sigma-Aldrich with the human recombinant protein or 100 μg total cell lysates from A549 cells. Lovastatin was used as a positive control, and SAHA as a negative control. HMGR activity under defined assay conditions, containing NADPH and HMG-CoA substrate in a final volume of 0.2 mL of 100 mM potassium phosphatate buffer (120 mM KCl, 1 mM EDTA, 5 mM DTT, pH 7.4), were initiated in the presence or absence (control) of test compounds dissolved in dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO). The rates of NADPH consumption were monitored every 20 seconds, for up to 10 minutes, by spectrophotometer at 37° C. and 340 nm.

Assay Description: Reductase Assay : The following procedure was followed using a HMG-CoA Reductase assay kit obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (catalogue number CS1090). The assay is based on the spectrophotometric measurement of the decrease in absorbance at 340 nm of NADPH in solution. A decrease in absorbance is caused by the oxidation of NADPH by the catalytic subunit of HMGR in the presence of the substrate HMG-CoA. Effective inhibition of the HMG-CoA leads to a reduction in oxidation of NADPH which in turn leads to a smaller reduction in the absorbance at 340 nm over time.
Tested in vitro for the inhibition of HMG-CoA reductase from partially purified microsomal preparations.

Assay Description: Reductase Assay : The following procedure was followed using a HMG-CoA Reductase assay kit obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (catalogue number CS1090). The assay is based on the spectrophotometric measurement of the decrease in absorbance at 340 nm of NADPH in solution. A decrease in absorbance is caused by the oxidation of NADPH by the catalytic subunit of HMGR in the presence of the substrate HMG-CoA. Effective inhibition of the HMG-CoA leads to a reduction in oxidation of NADPH which in turn leads to a smaller reduction in the absorbance at 340 nm over time.

Assay Description: Reductase Activity Assay: The HMGR activity was performed using HMG-CoA reductase assay kit from Sigma-Aldrich with the human recombinant protein or 100 μg total cell lysates from A549 cells. Lovastatin was used as a positive control, and SAHA as a negative control. HMGR activity under defined assay conditions, containing NADPH and HMG-CoA substrate in a final volume of 0.2 mL of 100 mM potassium phosphatate buffer (120 mM KCl, 1 mM EDTA, 5 mM DTT, pH 7.4), were initiated in the presence or absence (control) of test compounds dissolved in dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO). The rates of NADPH consumption were monitored every 20 seconds, for up to 10 minutes, by spectrophotometer at 37° C. and 340 nm.

Assay Description: Reductase Assay : The following procedure was followed using a HMG-CoA Reductase assay kit obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (catalogue number CS1090). The assay is based on the spectrophotometric measurement of the decrease in absorbance at 340 nm of NADPH in solution. A decrease in absorbance is caused by the oxidation of NADPH by the catalytic subunit of HMGR in the presence of the substrate HMG-CoA. Effective inhibition of the HMG-CoA leads to a reduction in oxidation of NADPH which in turn leads to a smaller reduction in the absorbance at 340 nm over time.

Assay Description: Reductase Assay : The following procedure was followed using a HMG-CoA Reductase assay kit obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (catalogue number CS1090). The assay is based on the spectrophotometric measurement of the decrease in absorbance at 340 nm of NADPH in solution. A decrease in absorbance is caused by the oxidation of NADPH by the catalytic subunit of HMGR in the presence of the substrate HMG-CoA. Effective inhibition of the HMG-CoA leads to a reduction in oxidation of NADPH which in turn leads to a smaller reduction in the absorbance at 340 nm over time.
